Dialogue: 0,0:50:40.00,0:50:44.72,Default,,0,0,0,,All these have different names in\NSanskrit.
Dialogue: 0,0:50:44.72,0:50:48.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Anybody here born in Sanskrit? Nobody.\NSo we won't speak sanskrites because
Dialogue: 0,0:50:48.96,0:50:54.16,Default,,0,0,0,,there's nobody here from Sanskrit.\NBut they all have great names, classical
Dialogue: 0,0:50:54.16,0:50:59.92,Default,,0,0,0,,names in Sanskrit.\NThe condition becomes established then
Dialogue: 0,0:50:59.92,0:51:06.24,Default,,0,0,0,,as a permanent\Nway of being with the energy of life
Dialogue: 0,0:51:06.24,0:51:10.96,Default,,0,0,0,,and eventually becomes independent of\Nany effort
Dialogue: 0,0:51:10.96,0:51:14.40,Default,,0,0,0,,whatsoever.\NThat's the value of the contemplative
Dialogue: 0,0:51:14.40,0:51:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,way of focusing on context. So as you\Nwalk around the world there's a letting
Dialogue: 0,0:51:21.68,0:51:27.76,Default,,0,0,0,,go of the content. So what we're talking\Nabout is disappearing
Dialogue: 0,0:51:27.76,0:51:31.52,Default,,0,0,0,,content. We're talking about the\Ndisappearing of content and the content
Dialogue: 0,0:51:31.52,0:51:39.35,Default,,0,0,0,,is the product of the ego\Nand as that is surrendered one becomes
Dialogue: 0,0:51:39.35,0:51:44.80,Default,,0,0,0,,the context and realizes one always was\Nthe context. Okay. So either in a
Dialogue: 0,0:51:44.80,0:51:49.76,Default,,0,0,0,,meditative state in a contemplative\Nstate one does the same thing when lets
Dialogue: 0,0:51:49.76,0:51:54.64,Default,,0,0,0,,go wanting to change things as they\Narise wanting to edit them wanting to
Dialogue: 0,0:51:54.64,0:52:00.24,Default,,0,0,0,,take a position about them wanting to\Ndevise an opinion about them wanting to
Dialogue: 0,0:52:00.24,0:52:06.72,Default,,0,0,0,,have a feeling about it.\NFinally all things are surrendered as
Dialogue: 0,0:52:06.72,0:52:11.59,Default,,0,0,0,,they arise and you walk about like you\Ndo in the woods. Mostly in the woods,
Dialogue: 0,0:52:11.59,0:52:15.52,Default,,0,0,0,,you're not going from one little Well,\Nyeah, people do. They do that, don't
Dialogue: 0,0:52:15.52,0:52:20.24,Default,,0,0,0,,they? They go from one little object to\Nanother. Oh, god. Look at this acorn.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:20.24,0:52:24.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Look at this squirrel. I guess they just\Nstay fixed right here in the center and
Dialogue: 0,0:52:24.40,0:52:29.59,Default,,0,0,0,,go from content to content.\NGenerally, a more meditative person gets
Dialogue: 0,0:52:29.59,0:52:33.92,Default,,0,0,0,,the space, the infinite peace and space\Nof nature. And that's why many people
Dialogue: 0,0:52:33.92,0:52:39.52,Default,,0,0,0,,prefer to meditate in nature because\Nit's easier to focus on context. There's
Dialogue: 0,0:52:39.52,0:52:42.64,Default,,0,0,0,,no television going. There's no\Nconversation.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:42.64,0:52:46.48,Default,,0,0,0,,There's no other people. There's no\Ntraffic. There's no distractions to pull
Dialogue: 0,0:52:46.48,0:52:51.04,Default,,0,0,0,,you back into\Nthe linear domain.
Dialogue: 0,0:52:51.04,0:52:58.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So to transcend then one's\Nidentification with the ego. We let go
Dialogue: 0,0:52:58.00,0:53:07.44,Default,,0,0,0,,of this form. And then what happens is\Nthe power of the context transforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:07.44,0:53:16.55,Default,,0,0,0,,The more we let go of the content, the\Ngreater is the effect of the context.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:16.55,0:53:22.31,Default,,0,0,0,,It's the power of context then that is\Nresponsible for our existence.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:22.31,0:53:27.04,Default,,0,0,0,,The ego would have you believe that it\Nis the source of your continued
Dialogue: 0,0:53:27.04,0:53:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,existence,\Nbut it's not. We exist in spite of the
Dialogue: 0,0:53:33.28,0:53:38.16,Default,,0,0,0,,ego, not because of it.\NWhat keeps you afloat is your buoyancy.
Dialogue: 0,0:53:38.16,0:53:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,And the buoyancy\Nis your relative energy as compared to
Dialogue: 0,0:53:43.04,0:53:49.35,Default,,0,0,0,,the field. The field is so powerful like\Na giant force of gravity that it
Dialogue: 0,0:53:49.35,0:53:53.11,Default,,0,0,0,,sustains you. And you think, well, it's\Nmy flailing in the water that's what's
Dialogue: 0,0:53:53.11,0:53:58.07,Default,,0,0,0,,keeping me afloat. What's keeping you\Nafloat is the specific gravity of salt
Dialogue: 0,0:53:58.07,0:54:02.72,Default,,0,0,0,,water,\Nnot your flailing around in the water.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:02.72,0:54:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,You understand? So it is safe to let it\Ngo. It is safe to let it go. And this
Dialogue: 0,0:54:09.04,0:54:14.72,Default,,0,0,0,,letting goeness of the belief systems of\Nthe ego are always accompanied by fear
Dialogue: 0,0:54:14.72,0:54:20.07,Default,,0,0,0,,that if I let this go, then the fear\Ncomes up. That's why you hang on to it.
Dialogue: 0,0:54:20.07,0:54:24.40,Default,,0,0,0,,So by the time you get to the final\Ndoorway, you will have had a lot of
Dialogue: 0,0:54:24.40,0:54:28.64,Default,,0,0,0,,experience in facing fear, surrendering\Nthat fear, facing fear, surrendering
Dialogue: 0,0:54:28.64,0:54:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,that fear. Each level of consciousness\Nthen
Dialogue: 0,0:54:33.28,0:54:39.52,Default,,0,0,0,,as you enter it is marvelous and and and\Nwonderful and then at the other end you
Dialogue: 0,0:54:39.52,0:54:44.80,Default,,0,0,0,,get again you see it's kept by fear.\NYou see that fear is now becomes the
Dialogue: 0,0:54:44.80,0:54:49.44,Default,,0,0,0,,block. So again you walk through the\Nnext fear. So anybody who's done a very
Dialogue: 0,0:54:49.44,0:54:55.11,Default,,0,0,0,,any very intensive meditation is aware\Nof that the sense of self reaches a
Dialogue: 0,0:54:55.11,0:54:59.59,Default,,0,0,0,,certain point and suddenly fear arises\Nand one feels like pulling back to the
Dialogue: 0,0:54:59.59,0:55:05.04,Default,,0,0,0,,previous identification of who you are.\NThe feeling if you let go at this point
Dialogue: 0,0:55:05.04,0:55:09.04,Default,,0,0,0,,you're going to become not me not you're\Ngoing to lose yourself lose your sense
Dialogue: 0,0:55:09.04,0:55:16.40,Default,,0,0,0,,of self. So that sense of losing\Nwho I am, my identity, my sense of self
Dialogue: 0,0:55:16.40,0:55:22.24,Default,,0,0,0,,arises over and over at each level. Each\None of these levels is capped by if I
Dialogue: 0,0:55:22.24,0:55:29.20,Default,,0,0,0,,let that go, I won't be me.\NYeah.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:29.20,0:55:33.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, the role of faith in\Nspiritual work, there's blind faith and
Dialogue: 0,0:55:33.83,0:55:40.40,Default,,0,0,0,,then there is more advanced faith.\NThere's the faith of naivity which leads
Dialogue: 0,0:55:40.40,0:55:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,many down the road to destruction.\NMisplay faith is uh the dark side's
Dialogue: 0,0:55:50.00,0:55:57.28,Default,,0,0,0,,greatest weapon.\NEvery great killer of humans.
Dialogue: 0,0:55:57.28,0:56:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.\NTo have faith in that which is in error
Dialogue: 0,0:56:03.52,0:56:10.40,Default,,0,0,0,,is deadly. So faith in and of itself\Nis not a virtue.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:10.40,0:56:15.11,Default,,0,0,0,,It's a stupidity\Nunless you know what it is you have
Dialogue: 0,0:56:15.11,0:56:20.16,Default,,0,0,0,,faith in.\NIf you calibrated Mallovich,
Dialogue: 0,0:56:20.16,0:56:24.88,Default,,0,0,0,,if you calibrated Hitler or if you\Ncalibrated Stalin, you calibrate Bin
Dialogue: 0,0:56:24.88,0:56:30.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Laden, I would not advise having faith\Nin them.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:30.79,0:56:36.31,Default,,0,0,0,,And yet many do. Isn't that correct?\NWhole nations put faith in the
Dialogue: 0,0:56:36.31,0:56:40.31,Default,,0,0,0,,megalomaniac over and over and over\Nagain.
Dialogue: 0,0:56:40.31,0:56:45.59,Default,,0,0,0,,In one lifetime, I don't remember how\Nmany put their whole nations put their
Dialogue: 0,0:56:45.59,0:56:51.28,Default,,0,0,0,,faith in a megalomaniac who sees to it\Nthat his entire nation is destroyed out
Dialogue: 0,0:56:51.28,0:56:56.55,Default,,0,0,0,,of his megalomania. And he will say they\Ndeserve it. They deserve it cuz they
Dialogue: 0,0:56:56.55,0:57:00.07,Default,,0,0,0,,lost the war. All Germans deserve to\Ndie.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:00.07,0:57:05.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Hitler wanted to burn down all Germany,\Ndidn't he? They don't deserve to live
Dialogue: 0,0:57:05.04,0:57:11.20,Default,,0,0,0,,because they lost the war.\NNo, faith is scary. You have to have
Dialogue: 0,0:57:11.20,0:57:15.68,Default,,0,0,0,,know what you're having faith in. So,\Nyou can only trust those who have gone
Dialogue: 0,0:57:15.68,0:57:21.68,Default,,0,0,0,,before who verified\Nthat the ice is okay to walk on there.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:21.68,0:57:26.48,Default,,0,0,0,,I wouldn't put faith in thin ice. So, a\Nlot of people do. And uh that's why not
Dialogue: 0,0:57:26.48,0:57:32.16,Default,,0,0,0,,too many people reach the ultimate goal.\NOne has to qualify
Dialogue: 0,0:57:32.16,0:57:37.44,Default,,0,0,0,,uh what that is that you're putting\Nfaith in faith however has a different
Dialogue: 0,0:57:37.44,0:57:44.55,Default,,0,0,0,,meaning. It means\Nfaith in it really means conviction.
Dialogue: 0,0:57:44.55,0:57:48.72,Default,,0,0,0,,All right for faith in the form of\Nconviction
Dialogue: 0,0:57:48.72,0:57:54.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the absolute certainty that one is\Nfollowing that which is absolutely the
Dialogue: 0,0:57:54.00,0:57:59.35,Default,,0,0,0,,truth.\NThat's a different kind of faith. Faith
Dialogue: 0,0:57:59.35,0:58:04.79,Default,,0,0,0,,in the proven. Oh, that's different.\NFaith in the proven. But I would not put
Dialogue: 0,0:58:04.79,0:58:10.31,Default,,0,0,0,,faith in that which is unproven.\NFaith in the proven.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:10.31,0:58:13.59,Default,,0,0,0,,How is surrendering everything to God\Ndifferent from passivity? Oh, that's a
Dialogue: 0,0:58:13.59,0:58:18.48,Default,,0,0,0,,clever question.\NIt's a psychological question actually.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:18.48,0:58:23.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Um,\Nsurrendering. What is one surrendering?
Dialogue: 0,0:58:23.59,0:58:27.83,Default,,0,0,0,,That's a good question. One is\Nsurrendering willfulness. One is
Dialogue: 0,0:58:27.83,0:58:34.55,Default,,0,0,0,,surrendering one's will.\NPassivity.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:34.55,0:58:40.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Passivity\Nuh is down here.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:40.96,0:58:46.16,Default,,0,0,0,,This is passivity.\NThe failure to take action where action
Dialogue: 0,0:58:46.16,0:58:50.55,Default,,0,0,0,,is called for.\NApathetic.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:50.55,0:58:54.72,Default,,0,0,0,,And there are some spiritual techniques\Nthat lead people into apathy.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:54.72,0:58:59.92,Default,,0,0,0,,They think they're detached. They're not\Ndetached. They're apathetic.
Dialogue: 0,0:58:59.92,0:59:05.59,Default,,0,0,0,,There's a group in Sedona.\NThey walk into a restaurant and
Dialogue: 0,0:59:05.59,0:59:14.79,Default,,0,0,0,,waitresses all go.\NThey never leave a tip for the waitress.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:14.79,0:59:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,They think that's wanting wanting\Npeople's approval, you know,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:20.00,0:59:24.31,Default,,0,0,0,,instead of seeing it as gratitude and\Nlove and acknowledgement,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:24.31,0:59:31.04,Default,,0,0,0,,you see. So, it's a miscalculation of\Nwhat it's about. All right? So, um no,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:31.04,0:59:38.16,Default,,0,0,0,,uh it would seem like passivity,\Nbut it seems like passivity only to ego.
Dialogue: 0,0:59:38.16,0:59:44.40,Default,,0,0,0,,You see, what is surrendered is the\Nwillfulness, the spiritual will. And so
Dialogue: 0,0:59:44.40,0:59:49.11,Default,,0,0,0,,all spiritual work is really\Nsurrendering one's will to God. One's
Dialogue: 0,0:59:49.11,0:59:55.44,Default,,0,0,0,,will to God. I want this side to win. I\Nwant that side to win. You know,
Dialogue: 0,0:59:55.44,1:00:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,uh so there's a willfulness. So what one\Nis surrendering is one's willfulness
Dialogue: 0,1:00:03.20,1:00:08.16,Default,,0,0,0,,that the world should be different than\Nit is. There is absolutely no reason at
Dialogue: 0,1:00:08.16,1:00:12.40,Default,,0,0,0,,all that the world should be different\Nthan it is.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:12.40,1:00:17.68,Default,,0,0,0,,There's not one single reason this world\Nshould or needs to be different than it
Dialogue: 0,1:00:17.68,1:00:24.24,Default,,0,0,0,,is.\NShould it be different than you perceive
Dialogue: 0,1:00:24.24,1:00:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,it? Well, that's different.\NSo, the best thing to do is not change
Dialogue: 0,1:00:30.00,1:00:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,the world, but change how you perceive\Nit. Think all the work you save
Dialogue: 0,1:00:33.44,1:00:38.79,Default,,0,0,0,,yourself.\NIf this is the great school, why do you
Dialogue: 0,1:00:38.79,1:00:43.28,Default,,0,0,0,,want to take it down? We just have to\Nbuild another school anywhere.
Dialogue: 0,1:00:43.28,1:00:51.28,Default,,0,0,0,,God evolves along with human\Nconsciousness. Isn't he lucky?
Dialogue: 0,1:00:51.28,1:00:56.07,Default,,0,0,0,,Happily his good luck is is that uh yeah\Nno
Dialogue: 0,1:00:56.07,1:01:00.07,Default,,0,0,0,,I think what the person means is our\Ncomprehension our understanding our
Dialogue: 0,1:01:00.07,1:01:05.04,Default,,0,0,0,,awareness of the reality of God. Yes it\Nvery definitely evolves with human
Dialogue: 0,1:01:05.04,1:01:09.35,Default,,0,0,0,,consciousness as we see over on the left\Nhand side here.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:09.35,1:01:19.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah, God does improve.\NGod's going to throw you in hell. He
Dialogue: 0,1:01:19.83,1:01:24.79,Default,,0,0,0,,hates you because you're a sinner. He\Ncondemns you to eternal damnation. Here
Dialogue: 0,1:01:24.79,1:01:28.24,Default,,0,0,0,,he you're so distasteful. He doesn't\Nwant anything to do with you. Here he's
Dialogue: 0,1:01:28.24,1:01:32.88,Default,,0,0,0,,just punitive. He's only interested in\Npunishing people. And here he denies
Dialogue: 0,1:01:32.88,1:01:41.52,Default,,0,0,0,,himself to you. You call out for him. Oh\NGod, help me.
Dialogue: 0,1:01:41.52,1:01:48.64,Default,,0,0,0,,cuz you're just a worm. So\Nhere he gets even with you for screwing
Dialogue: 0,1:01:48.64,1:01:52.88,Default,,0,0,0,,up.\NHere he couldn't care less. Here's the
Dialogue: 0,1:01:52.88,1:01:59.68,Default,,0,0,0,,god of indifference. Sort of the Sartra.\NSort of Sartra. Ser calibrates about 220
Dialogue: 0,1:01:59.68,1:02:06.24,Default,,0,0,0,,or something. Anyway, uh he couldn't\Ncare less. That's God is an indifferent.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:06.24,1:02:10.40,Default,,0,0,0,,God is like space. If you're there,\Nthat's fine. If you're not there, it's
Dialogue: 0,1:02:10.40,1:02:15.35,Default,,0,0,0,,fine. Space couldn't care less.\NHere we start getting into freedom,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:15.35,1:02:21.83,Default,,0,0,0,,courage, the courage of choice. In other\Nwords, here we see opportunity,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:21.83,1:02:28.00,Default,,0,0,0,,support, inspiration,\Nabsolutely merciful.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:28.00,1:02:33.04,Default,,0,0,0,,For God not to be merciful, he would\Nhave to be judgmental. to be judgmental,
Dialogue: 0,1:02:33.04,1:02:37.20,Default,,0,0,0,,he would have to suffer from dualistic\Nperceptual distortions.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:37.20,1:02:42.07,Default,,0,0,0,,If he suffered from dualistic perceptual\Ndistortions, he couldn't be God. And if
Dialogue: 0,1:02:42.07,1:02:47.28,Default,,0,0,0,,he isn't God, you don't have to be\Nafraid. So, anything that's
Dialogue: 0,1:02:47.28,1:02:53.35,Default,,0,0,0,,anything that is judgmental, you can\Nforget about because he's as bad as you
Dialogue: 0,1:02:53.35,1:02:56.88,Default,,0,0,0,,are. In fact, you're probably higher\Nthan he is.
Dialogue: 0,1:02:56.88,1:03:01.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So these horrible gods that wait for you\Ncoming out of ancient scriptures are,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:01.92,1:03:06.88,Default,,0,0,0,,you know, from the unconscious\Nanthropomorphic projections,
Dialogue: 0,1:03:06.88,1:03:12.96,Default,,0,0,0,,at least at least God is inspirational\Nand hopeful. Yeah.
Dialogue: 0,1:03:12.96,1:03:18.40,Default,,0,0,0,,And because you're at least merciful to\Nthat which lives, you can presume God is
Dialogue: 0,1:03:18.40,1:03:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,at least as high and evolved as you are.\NAnybody can forgive your mother-in-law
Dialogue: 0,1:03:29.68,1:03:35.44,Default,,0,0,0,,or your his ex-wife or whatever.\NAll right. And as you do this, you
Dialogue: 0,1:03:35.44,1:03:41.76,Default,,0,0,0,,finally come into wisdom. The difficulty\Nwith which we see in politics mainly is
Dialogue: 0,1:03:41.76,1:03:48.64,Default,,0,0,0,,in in in its impact on life is that it's\Ncorrect as far as content go but it what
Dialogue: 0,1:03:48.64,1:03:53.28,Default,,0,0,0,,negates it is the context.\NYou know everybody's out with a parade
Dialogue: 0,1:03:53.28,1:03:59.35,Default,,0,0,0,,about their freedoms. I'm a taxpayer.\NI'm free to picnic in the woods. That's
Dialogue: 0,1:03:59.35,1:04:04.64,Default,,0,0,0,,my right. They're entitled. They have\Nrights. My right to picnic in the woods
Dialogue: 0,1:04:04.64,1:04:07.52,Default,,0,0,0,,except when there's a drought. No,\Nyou're not allowed to picnic in the
Dialogue: 0,1:04:07.52,1:04:11.35,Default,,0,0,0,,woods during a drought when there's\Nextreme fire danger and millions of
Dialogue: 0,1:04:11.35,1:04:16.24,Default,,0,0,0,,acres are already burning and houses are\Nburning. No. So
Dialogue: 0,1:04:16.24,1:04:21.20,Default,,0,0,0,,all such things then are subject to\Ncontent. It's only so under certain
Dialogue: 0,1:04:21.20,1:04:26.96,Default,,0,0,0,,conditions. That's sort of the basis of\Nsituational ethics. A thing is ethical
Dialogue: 0,1:04:26.96,1:04:33.92,Default,,0,0,0,,or unethical under what conditions?\NThat which is pedestrian ethics then
Dialogue: 0,1:04:33.92,1:04:38.96,Default,,0,0,0,,fails to reach the point of wisdom\Nbecause the point of wisdom what's the
Dialogue: 0,1:04:38.96,1:04:42.64,Default,,0,0,0,,difference between the intelligent and\Nwisdom.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:42.64,1:04:48.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh well wisdom where is wisdom?\NWisdom
Dialogue: 0,1:04:48.64,1:04:54.40,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't know where he went. Wisdom is up\Nhere. Okay. Okay.
Dialogue: 0,1:04:54.40,1:05:01.44,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. Wisdom then takes into takes\Ninto account context. context, the
Dialogue: 0,1:05:01.44,1:05:06.24,Default,,0,0,0,,foolishness of the youth that did it or\Nthe culture in which he comes, you know,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:06.24,1:05:09.59,Default,,0,0,0,,totally changes the meaning and\Nsignificance of that thing. For this
Dialogue: 0,1:05:09.59,1:05:14.48,Default,,0,0,0,,person to do it, it would be heinous.\NFor this person to do it, it's probably,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:14.48,1:05:19.44,Default,,0,0,0,,you know, it's stupidity. So, we\Nconstantly modify it. And to pretend
Dialogue: 0,1:05:19.44,1:05:24.72,Default,,0,0,0,,that that is not so is the pitfall of\Ncertain political positions which don't
Dialogue: 0,1:05:24.72,1:05:28.24,Default,,0,0,0,,see that in times of war things are\Ndifferent than times of peace, in times
Dialogue: 0,1:05:28.24,1:05:35.11,Default,,0,0,0,,of drought. You're right. As a picnicer\Nis different, you know,
Dialogue: 0,1:05:35.11,1:05:39.83,Default,,0,0,0,,if nonlinear dynamics is a product of\Nthe 400s, it isn't. So that answers that
Dialogue: 0,1:05:39.83,1:05:51.92,Default,,0,0,0,,question.\NThe intellectual construction in
